summary: That was the day without a dawn. Slowly the sky lightened around them, but they never saw the sun. Black turned to grey, and...
text: That was the day without a dawn. Slowly the sky lightened around them, but they never saw the sun. Black turned to grey, and colors crept timidly back into the world. The soldier pines were dressed in somber greens, the broadleafs in russets and faded golds already beginning to brown.
source: Arya Stark, A Storm of Swords

summary: Arya and Dany are great characters to look up to. Both are strong young girls who faced so much trauma in their stories and yet...
body:
Arya and Dany are great characters to look up to. Both are strong young girls who faced so much trauma in their stories and yet they still kind people at their core. 

Also, the fact that neither adheres to their patriarchal society’s standards for womanhood is another reason they make such great role models- because they teach girls from everywhere that they  don’t need to be what their sexist society demands, in order to become important or be a great person overall. Arya and Dany just being themselves is enough.

summary: I think that Game of Thrones removing a lot of it’s female characters internal struggle, vulnerability and feminine qualities...
body: I think that Game of Thrones removing a lot of it’s female characters internal struggle, vulnerability and feminine qualities was a mistake. The show’s idea of a “strong” female character is one who can physically fight, can kill others or/and can back talk. The female characters who couldn’t do any of these things were forced into onto becoming a character capable of some or all of these things and the ones who fit generally more with their idea of a strong female character had every of their quality that didn’t fit with it removed. However, Brienne’s naivety that allow her to see the brighter side of corrupt systems, Sansa’s unwavering empathy that extended to people who don’t deserve it, Arya’s constant fear and sadness, and Dany’s wishes of having a childhood that she never got to experience and a home where she could feel safe made them feel real, and either were parts of them that made them strong, or were parts of them that made it amazing that they were able to continue without giving up. It’s evident that the show feeds into this already prescribed idea of what makes a woman strong (basically consists of having many traditionally masculine traits), rather than challenge that idea like the books do.
